<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Which best describes the difference between real and nominal GDP?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Real GDP includes imports, nominal GDP doesn't</option>
            <option letter="b">Real GDP adjusts for inflation, nominal GDP doesn't</option>
            <option letter="c">Real GDP measures quantity, nominal GDP measures quality</option>
            <option letter="d">Real GDP excludes services, nominal GDP includes them</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Real GDP adjusts for price level changes (inflation) to measure actual changes in production, while nominal GDP measures production at current prices without adjusting for inflation.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does depreciation affect GDP measurement?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Increases GDP by the amount of depreciation</option>
            <option letter="b">Is subtracted from gross investment to get net investment</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on GDP measurement</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects real GDP</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Depreciation is subtracted from gross investment to calculate net investment, which shows the actual increase in the capital stock. GDP includes gross investment before depreciation.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to potential GDP when the average skill level of workers increases?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Potential GDP decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Potential GDP increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Potential GDP stays the same</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects actual GDP</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in worker skill levels represents an improvement in human capital, which increases potential GDP by enhancing the economy's productive capacity at all price levels.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in the minimum wage affect teenage unemployment?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Always decreases teenage unemployment</option>
            <option letter="b">Tends to increase teenage unemployment</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on teenage unemployment</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects adult unemployment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in the minimum wage tends to increase teenage unemployment because teenagers often have less experience and skills, making them less likely to be hired at the higher wage rate.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
